# Define the columns to be imputed
columns = ['Isolation_Index_Non_Hispanic_Asian', 'Isolation_Index_Non-Hispanic_Black', 
           'Isolation_Index_Hispanic', 'Access_to_Exercise_Opportunities_Percent', 
           'Primary_Care_Physicians_Rate_per_100']

# Iterate over each column to impute
for col in columns:
    imputer = KNNImputer(n_neighbors=5)
    imputer_data = imputer.fit_transform(merge_data[[col]])  # double brackets to keep it as DataFrame
    merge_data[col] = imputer_data.ravel()  # Flatten the array back into the original DataFrame column
In [9]:
# Since the food environment features appear to be missing at random, I will fill the missing values with the mean value for each state


# Calculate the mean Fast_Food_Restaurant value for each state
state_means_1 = merge_data.groupby('State')['Fast_Food_Restaurant'].transform('mean')

# Fill missing values in Fast_Food_Restaurant with the mean of their respective state
merge_data['Fast_Food_Restaurant'] = merge_data['Fast_Food_Restaurant'].fillna(state_means_1)

state_means_2 = merge_data.groupby('State')['Food_environ_index'].transform('mean')
merge_data['Food_environ_index'] = merge_data['Fast_Food_Restaurant'].fillna(state_means_2)

Fast_Food_Restaurant and Food_environ_index: Both have a VIF of inf, which suggests that each may be perfectly predicted by a combination of the other independent variables in the model. It's crucial to investigate this further. It may require dropping one of the variables or combining them somehow to remove the perfect multicollinearity.

clean_data_2 = clean_data_num.copy()
for column in clean_data_2.select_dtypes(include=['float64', 'int64']).columns:
    Q1 = clean_data_2[column].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = clean_data_2[column].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

    # Here we are updating clean_data_3 by filtering out the outliers
    clean_data_2 = clean_data_2[(clean_data_2[column] >= lower_bound) & (clean_data_2[column] <= upper_bound)]

In [31]:
def evaluate_and_plot_model(model, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, model_name):
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train)
    y_test_pred = model.predict(X_test)

    print(f"\n{model_name} Training Set Performance:")
    print("R-squared:", r2_score(y_train, y_train_pred))
    print("Mean Absolute Error (MAE):", mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_train_pred))
    print("Mean Squared Error (MSE):", mean_squared_error(y_train, y_train_pred))
    print("Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE):", np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_train, y_train_pred)))

    print(f"\n{model_name} Test Set Performance:")
    print("R-squared:", r2_score(y_test, y_test_pred))
    print("Mean Absolute Error (MAE):", mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_test_pred))
    print("Mean Squared Error (MSE):", mean_squared_error(y_test, y_test_pred))
    print("Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE):", np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_test_pred)))

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.scatter(y_test, y_test_pred, label=f'{model_name} Predictions')
    plt.xlabel('True Values')
    plt.ylabel('Predictions')
    plt.title(f'{model_name} Predictions vs True Values')
    plt.legend()
    plt.plot([min(y_test), max(y_test)], [min(y_test), max(y_test)], color='red') # Line for perfect predictions
    plt.show()

# Because the SVR model is stable on both the training and test data set, so I choose the SVR to go through a simple tuning.
pipeline = make_pipeline(StandardScaler(), SVR())

# Define the parameter grid
param_grid = {
    'svr__C': [0.1, 1, 10, 100],  # Experiment with these values
    'svr__epsilon': [0.01, 0.1, 0.2, 0.5]
}

# Setup the grid search
grid_search = GridSearchCV(pipeline, param_grid, cv=5, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')

# Fit grid search
grid_search.fit(X, y)

print("Best parameters found: ", grid_search.best_params_)
print("Best cross-validation score: ", -grid_search.best_score_)

# Use the best estimator to make predictions
y_pred = grid_search.predict(X_test)

print("Test Set Evaluation")
print("R-squared:", r2_score(y_test, y_pred))
print("Mean Absolute Error (MAE):", mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred))
print("Mean Squared Error (MSE):", mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))
print("Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE):", np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)))

y_pred_train = grid_search.predict(X_train)

print("\nTraining Set Evaluation")
print("R-squared:", r2_score(y_train, y_pred_train))
print("Mean Absolute Error (MAE):", mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_pred_train))
print("Mean Squared Error (MSE):", mean_squared_error(y_train, y_pred_train))
print("Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE):", np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_train, y_pred_train)))

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
